	<h2 class="itemTitle">
		
		What is an application container?
				<!-- Featured flag -->
		<span>
			<sup>
				Featured			</sup>
		</span>
			</h2>
	<div class="top-status-bar">
		
	
	
		<!-- Date created -->
	<span class="itemDateCreated">
	<i class="fa fa-clock-o" aria-hidden="true"></i>
		December 04, 2018	</span>
				<!-- Item category -->
		<div class="itemCategory">
			<span><i class="fa fa-folder-o" aria-hidden="true"></i></span>
			<a href="/smartit/index.php/en/component/k2/itemlist/category/8-programing">Programing</a>
		</div>
			
	
	
			</div>
	
	
	

	</div>
		
		
		

		
		<!-- Item text -->
		<div class="itemFullText">
			<p>The Application Container is a standalone software package that contains everything you need to run. It can easily be run in any compatible environment without the need for a complicated installation. After running, the container runs in its own space, dedicated to the host operating system. It has its own network interface (IP address) and its own file system. The best-known application container platform is <a href="https://www.docker.com/what-container" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> Docker </a>. Application container launch technology is very similar for example OpenVZ project, it can even be compared to a virtual server, but its use is different in this case.</p>
<h3>Basic Principles</h3>
<p>Only one process should run in the container. For PHP applications, for example, we would run PHP-FPM in one container, and in the second nginx, which will be connected to PHP via TCP port. The application communicates with the outside world via TCP (or UDP). The container has out-of-print ports that respond either to Internet connections or other containers. The visibility of selected busses is provided by the host operating system, for example, through reverse proxy or NAT. The application should be configurable through environment variables, such as the address and login data of the database, which is easy to set up when the container is started up. In addition, it should log on to standard or error output (stdout, stderr), the host system should handle these outputs. The application should not use the file system to store persistent data. Ideally use different kinds of databases (SQL, redis, etc.), or S3 to store uploaded files, for example. However, exceptions are often made from this rule, so if necessary, we can connect volumes from a shared storage container to the container.</p>
<h3>What is a good application container?</h3>
<p>I'll just run an application container in any environment without the need for installation. For example, for docker containers, just have a docker installed on the server, and I can run any container. So, the developer can run and install an application container on his laptop under the docker, which he then uploads to the repository and can be deployed to the test environment or to production without further modification. It saves the hurdle of "<em> but works well for me " If you do not use the container development benefits yet, we can build a container build environment from your classic app </em></p>		</div>

		
